  "opinion": "As a school teacher in Bari, I've witnessed firsthand how stereotype threat can quietly undermine students' potential in STEM fields. Stereotype threat isn't just a theoretical concept—it's the anxiety that arises when individuals fear their performance might confirm negative stereotypes about their group. For instance, when a girl in my class hesitates to raise her hand in math class because she worries she'll 'prove' she's not good at it, or when a boy avoids physics problems due to the stereotype that 'only girls are good at math,' this isn't just about individual confidence—it's about systemic barriers that have deep roots in societal expectations. I've seen this play out in my classroom: students who belong to underrepresented groups often perform worse on tests not because they lack ability, but because of the mental load of constantly proving themselves. Addressing stereotype threat requires more than just awareness; it demands intentional, culturally responsive teaching practices. I believe we should actively challenge stereotypes by normalizing diverse role models in STEM—showing students that people from all backgrounds have thrived in these fields. For example, sharing stories of Italian scientists or women who've overcome similar barriers can make the concept feel more relatable and less intimidating. Additionally, creating a classroom environment where mistakes are celebrated as learning opportunities, rather than failures, helps reduce the pressure students feel. As someone who values quiet, thoughtful engagement (as reflected in my low extraversion score and high conscientiousness), I've found that these strategies work best when they're implemented with patience and consistency. Ultimately, addressing stereotype threat isn't about fixing students—it's about fostering an environment where every child feels capable of reaching their full potential.",
